{"/service/ndnp/mb/batch_mb_basil_ver01/data/sn83020847/00517171098/1930090401/0505.xml":{"full_text":"FINANCIAL NEWS\nThe Business Trend\nFirst Signs of Fall Upturn\nLabor day can be celebrated with\nunquestionable assurances that signs\nof an upturn in business from mid\nsummer levels have appeared. Ab\nsence of such signs at this date would\nbe extremely disconcerting, not to say\nalarming. General business activity\nhad been for about a month at the\nlowest ebb since the 1921 'depression.\nContinuation of such a rate after the\nbeginning of the fall season would be\nserious, for the country in the mean\ntime has gained materially in popu\nlation, in productive capacity and in\nproperty investment. There is as yet\nno indication of what the fall will\nbring in the way of business revival,\nbut expectations are not pitched high.\nModerate recovery from midsummer\ndullness is fairly certain; an advance\nfrom the average levels of the year\nwould cause surprise.\nThe two indexes which reveal a,\ngain from midsummer lows are the\nreports of steel output and railroad\ncar loadings. The Iron Age has re\nported a gain of 1 per cent in steel\ningot production for two successive\n\u25a0weeks. While there is, as usual, a\nslight disagreement between the Iron\nAge\u2019s estimate of ingot production and\nthe Dow-Jones estimate, both agree\nIn showing an advance. That is the\nimportant thing, and little attention\nneed be given to the fact that the\n.Iron Age places the total volume of\ningots at 54 per cent of capacity and\nthe Dow-Jones report at 58 per cent.\nThe Iron Age\u2019s Interpretation of the\nsteel outlook is, however, very con-\nVservative. As yet there has been very\nslight increase in mill bookings, and\nprices of finished steel have under\ngone further declines, though more\nresistance to the lower price trend is\n.-apparent. The steel industry is said\nto see little chance for a marked re\ncovery in business this year, \"but\nthere is growing adherence to the\nbelief that the autumn months will\n*at least bring some measure of sea\nsonal improvement.\u201d\nIt is possible that there has been\nsome acceleration of ingot output in\nanticipation of fall demand for\nfinished steel, and with definite in\ntention to hearten business sentiment\nin all lines. This would not appear\nto be the case, however, as the im\n\u2019provement in steel operations has\nbeen accompanied by rather sub\nstantial advances in steel scrap, which\nbetokens genuine demand. Moreover,\nthere has been an increase in rail\nroad loadings of miscellaneous\n\u2019freight\u2014an index which corresponds\npretty closely to shipments of finished\nsteel. The railroad loadings report\nfor the second full week of August,\ntogether with indications of what the\nthird week\u2019s loadings will be, js the\nI most comprehensive evidence that the\nGOV ROY 1 YOUNG,\nFEDERAL RESERVE,\nr RESIGNS POSITION\nTo Head Federal Reserve\nBank of Boston Hoover\nExpresses Regret in Ac\ncepting Resignation\nFrom The Republican\u2019*\nWashington bureau\nWashington, Aug. 27\u2014Roy A. Young,\ngovernor and member ot the Federal\nReserve board, is to become governor\nof the Federal Reserve bank of Bos\n\u2019\u2019ton, and his resignation, effective Sep\ntember 1, today was accepted by Pres\nident Hoover, In his letter of resig\nnation Mr Y'oung emphasized that \u201cfor\nfeome time it has been necessary for\niW to consider accepting a more re\nmunerative position.\u201d And the Presi\ndent In accepting his resignation said:\n\u201cYou have made a great sacrifice dur\nIng the last three years, and I do not\nbelieve that I ought to ask you to\nI continue to do so. Your reasons are\nI sufficiently compelling to forbid my in\ni sistlng that you remain, much as I am\ni tempted to do so.\u201d\ni The remainder.ot Present Hoover\u2019s\nletter was as follows:\nF \"You have the right to feel that you\nhave rendered real public service. You\nbrought to the position of governor\nsound banking judgment based on\nmany years ot experience and a com\nprehensive knowledge of financial, in\nl.dustrlal and agricultural conditions\nthroughout the country and ot our\nnational banking system. In very dif\nficult times you have performed the\nimportant duties ot your office with\nexcellent judgment, tact and courage,\nAnd I shall find it difficult to replace\nyou. I wish to express not only my\nown appreciation of your devoted pub\nlic service, but my conviction that\nycur resignation will be received with\nregret by the country as a whole. It\nis my understanding that you wish\nsyour resignation to be effective Sep\ntember 1, which Is agreeable to me.\n\u201cWith best wishes for your future\nsuccess and happiness.\"\nGov Young's Letter\nIn his letter of resignation Gov\n'Young explained that he has refrained\nI from retiring from the federal service\nat an earlier date \"because I have felt\nthat I was not in a position to accept\nemployment elsewhere, regardless of\nhow attractive an offer might be, when\nthe credit conditions of the country\nwere strained or disturbed. Obviously,\nthese factors have limited the oppor\ntunities.\n\"However, It Is clearly evident that\nthe credit structure of the country is\n.in an easy and exceptionally strong\nposition, and an opportunity has come\nto me from the directors of the Fed\neral Reserve bank of Boston, that is,\nthey have honored me by offering to\nme the governorship of that bank, a\n^responsibility that I am very anxious\nto undertake and feel that I should. I,\ntherefore, am tendering my resigna\ntion as governor and a member of the\nFederal Reserve board to become ef\nfective as soon as accepted by you.\n\u201cI am taking this action with many\nitregrets because I have thoroughly en\njoyed the three years 1 have been a\nmember of the board. And that 1\nhave profited greatly In experience, as\nsociations and friondshlns there can be\nno doubt. I am most graceful to every\none who has made It possible for me\nto accumulate such valued assets, and\n1 particularly take this opportunity to\nlow point of the midsummer has\npassed.\nLow Point Probably Passed\nFor the week ended August 16 the\nrailroads loaded 923,873 cars, a gain\nof 18,666 over the previous week.\nCompared with the figures for the\nsame week in 192\u00bb and 1928, the\ntotal of 923,873 cars is not very im\npressive, for it shows a reduction of\n179,744 and 135,086 cars, respectively.\nAs the railroads have lost some traffic\nto trucks within the one-year and\ntwo-year periods this decrease does\nnot necessarily denote an exactly\ncorresponding decrease in the coun\ntry\u2019s business, but the measurement\nis close enough for practical purposes.\nThe thing to note is that the increase\nof 18,666 over the previous week was\nthe first gain sirice July 19. and\nshowed a smaller percentage of de\ncrease from the corresponding week\nof 1929 and 1928. A single week\u2019s\nfigures may reflect accidental fluctua\ntions and are not to be taken as con\nclusive, but as the Pennsylvania rail\nroad reports a 2635-car gain for the\nweek ended August 23 (for which full\nreports will not be published until\nWednesday), it seems likely that the\nadvance will be sustained through at\nleast a second week and perhaps in\ndefinitely. If this proves to be the\ncase, the low point of the midsummer\ndullness will have been fixed in the\nweek ended August 9.\nThe stock market, which had an\nextra half holiday on Saturday, sup\nplied a clew to what may be expect\ned after Labor day. There will be\nanother energetic effort to boost\nstocks on the theory that business is\nrecovering. This movement tvill have\nlittle to do with actual business, but\nwill be entirely a maneuver of specu\nlators who have bought or will buy\nstocks with the expectation of un\nloading them at a profit. A similar\nmovement in July collapsed after\ngoing ahead two or three weeks. At\nthe present time there is, of course,\nthe certainty of some Improvement in\nbusiness, and it is likely that any\nnormal fall advance will be magnified\nby the propagandists of speculation\nuntil it appears like another forward\nmovement.\nDividends and Interest\nThere has been considerable further\ncutting of corporation dividend rates,\nyet so many initial payments have\nbeen made since a year ago that one\nlist of dividends and interest disburse\nments at the beginning of September\nshotvs a total only\u2019 $6,000,000 less than\nlast year. As dividends begin to drop\nthe question is asked whether so\nmany should have been raised a year\nago. A more critical question is\nwhether there should have been so\nmany splitups of stock in corpora-,\ntions seasoned and unseasc^jed. An\nother quesetion is whether the various\nmergers *n industrial, food and utility\nUnes were invariably accompanied by\nthe creation of a conservative capital\nstructure, capable of weathering a\nperiod of declining prices and un\ncertain volume of business.\nthank you for the many things you\nhave done, both officially and private\nly. You have been most considerate\non all occasions and I am deeply in\ndebted to you.\u201d\nLUMBER MILL BURNED\nIN NORTHERN NEW YORK\nFlames Destroy Saranac\n(N. Y.) Plant Damage\nEstimated at $250,000\nSaranac Lake, N. Y\u201e Aug. 31\u2014\n(AP) \u2014Fire which started last night\nand which firemen from four towns\nbattled until 5 this afternoon def\nstroyed Branch Callahan's lumber\nmill, one of the largest in northern\nNew York. Police estimated the loss\nat $250,000.\nThe flames, starting in a large\nframe barn, swept through a garage,\nstorehouses, sheds and an office build\ning into the mill. The fire fighters,\nhampered by low water pressure, had\ndifficulty in preventing the flames\nfrom spreading to nearby dwellings,\nand a garage, an automobile sales\nroom and an apartment house were\ndamaged.\nSaranac Lake firemen called tor\nhelp from Malone, Tupper Lake and\nLake Placid.\nBranch Callahan's mill, in the\nheart of the city, was destroyed with\nIts entire stock of lumber in 1901 in\nthe most disastrous fire in this resort\ncity\u2019s history.\nCENSORING THE STAGE\ntN>w York Times.]\nIn the old play jury method several\nmistakes appeared in practice which\nEquity believes can be eliminated. Es\nsentially, the plan is sound in that it\ncloses an objectionable play quietly\nand finally. Equity, by ordering all\nthe actors to quit, has the absolute\npower ot life or death. There is\nneither time nor opportunity for the\nnotoriety which, under the Wales law,\nhas turned several insignificant pieces\nof unquestioned stupidity and ques\ntionable morals into money-makers.\nTe jurors will not be known to th'e\npublic. They will be chosen from a\nlist of 200 to be supplied by the Amer\nican Arbitration association. A com\nmittee of three actors, three dramatists\nand three producing managers will\nselect five from this' body to repre\nsent the public, and two engaged in\ntheatrical work of some kind to rep\nresent the theater. Plays complained\nof will be visited by this jury, and it\nwill exonerate the play, order changes\nmade, or order it closed. It all this Is\ndone without notice to the newspa\npers or any of the hullaballoo that\nhas Invariably increased receipts for\nplays raided by the police, every one\nwill have fair treatment. No harm\nwill be done the reputation ot players\nwho/not willingly participate in a\ndirty play, and good plays will not\nsuffer the competition of productions\npuffed up by court notoriety.\nThis plan comes as close to self\nregulation as any could, and the op\nponents ot censorship should rally to\nit. So, too, should those who have fa\nvored censorship, for it stands a far i\nbetter chance of getting the results\nthey want than anything which has\nbeen tried. The recently demonstrated\nwillingness of the producers to see\nfurther than the ends ot their noses,\nano help the public to get seats at\nsomething resembling bqx-ofllce prices\nis another factor in the present state\nof affairs looking toward a success\nful operation ot Equity's plan. Equity\nhas the power to enforce It without\ntheir approval, hut It will work more I\nSmoothly and be much pleasanter all\naround it they aid by keeping their i\nshows tree from obscenity.\nTHE SPRINGFIELD WEEKLY REPUBLICAN: SPRINGFIELD, MASS.: THURSDAY. SEPTEMBER 4, 1020\nTUMBLE REPORTED\nIN NEW ENGLAND\u2019S\nINDUSTRY IN JULY\nActivity at Lowest Level in\nRecent Years, Review by\nBoston Federal Reserve\nBank Declares\nBoston, Aug. 31\u2014(AP)\u2014 Industrial\nactivity in New England in July was\nat the lowest level in recent years\naccording to the monthly review of\nthe Federal Reserve bank of Boston,\nreleased today.\n\u201cAlthough there is usually less ac\ntivity im the midsummer months, the\nrecession this year between June and\nJuly was of more than the usual sea\nsonal amount,\u201d the review says.\n\u201cQuiet conditions prevailed in prac\ntically all lines of industry, and about\nthe same volume of manufacturing,\nin the aggregate, took place in July\nas in that month In 1924.\n\u201cSevere Decline'\u2019 Noted\n\u201cDuring the first seven months in\nthe current year there has been a\nsevere decline in consumer purchasing\npower tn New Englnad, as is indi\ncated in the fact that estimated Wage\npayments in more than 1000 identical\nmanufacturing establishments in Mas\nsachusetts were approximately $14,-\n000,000 less in the period from Jan\nuary, through July than in the corre\nsponding period a year ago. A similar\ncurtailment in actual purchasing Mbs\nnot been evident until recently, since\nMassachusetts department stores re\nported sales for the first halt of this\nyear as of the same volume as irt that\nperiod of 1929. In June and July,\nhowever, there were declines of about\n7 and 6 per cent tram a year ago, and\nretail trade appals to be following\nthe downward swing in the industrial\nactivity.\n\"Boston department store sales dur\ning the first half of August were less\nthan those in this period a year ago.\n\u201cIn July New England textile ac\ntivity declined still more. Cotton con\nsumption declined to the smallest\nmonthly amount since the records\nstarted in 1919, and there was a sharp\ndrop in silk machinery activity. Con\nsumption of raw wool in this district\nin July increased by a little less than\nthe customary seasonal amount. The\nvolume of boots and shoes produced in\nNew England in July was about the\nsame as in June, but usually there is\na slight increase between these two\nmonths. There was a decline, how\never, between July, 1930, and July,\n1929, amounting to more than 22 per\ncent. Shoe production in the entire\ncountry during July declined about 21\nper cent from that month a year\nago.\n\"The building Industry was unusual\nly quiet in July, and during the first\nseven months of this year total new\ncontracts awarded in New England\nwas about 14 per cent less than in\nthe corresponding period last year.\nThe volume (square feet) of commer\ncial and industrial building in this dis\ntrict in July was the smallest in a\nnine-year period. Total car loadings\nin New England has reflected the gen\nerally slow condition of industry and\ntrade and in the first six weeks of\nthe third quarter declined approxi\nmately 17 per cent from those during\nthe corresponding period a year ago.\n\u201cRegistrations of new automobiles\nin New England have been lower each\nmonth this year than in the corre\nsponding months of 1929, and at about\nthe end of the seventh month were\nabout 23 per cent behind.\n\"The percentage of regular accounts\noutstanding at the first of July col\nlected during July in New England\ndepartment stores was 44.7 compared\nyith 49.8 in July, 1929, and 48.3 in\n1928.\u201d\nSEES BUILDING AS KEY\nTO BUSINESS REVIVAL\nDodge Corporation Statisti\ncian Doubts Full Recovery\nBefore 1932\nNew York, Sept. I\u2014(AP) \u2014L. Seth\nSchnitman, chief statistician of the F.\nW. Dodge corporation, says in an ar\nticle in the Architectural Record that\nresidential building is the key to re\nvival in the construction industry and,\nthrough it, recovery in general busi\nness.\nThe extensive activity in the indus\ntry during the years after the 1920-21\ndepression received its principal im\npetus froip residential building, Mr\nSchnitman points out, but doubts that\nit will be restored to its primary posi\ntion before 1932.\nHe views as encouraging the liquid\nation of the oversupply of housing\nthat followed the war, .and says the\ntime is apparently approaching when\nbetter balance between supply and\ndemand may be expected. The stage\nis being set, he declares, for creation\nof large housing corporation* rivaling\nmany of our large industrials in point\nof size. Their principal function will\nbe the redevelopment ot existing cen\nters on a reasonable rental basis,, he\nbelieves.\nBOULDER DAM\n[Pennsylvania Farmer.]\nWork on Boulder dam has started.\nThe first 10 million of 165 million\ndollars of taxpayers' money has been\nappropriated by Congress and the\nproject which is to raise the sur\nface ot a river 600 feet begun. It\nwill cream a reservoir 86 miles long\nwhich will hold enough water to\ncover 30.000,000 acres of land a foot\ndeep. Machinery to produce a mil\nlion horsepower will be installed. This\nis doing things in a big way and\nwill be looked on with pride by many\npeople, especially the comparatively\ntew who will benefit by It. The fact\nthat it will irrigate 400,000 acres of\nfertile hut now dry southern Califor\nnia land will not be greeted with en\nthusiasm by food producers who at\npresent face plenty of competition.\nBut the thing to give us pause is that\nhere our government is stepping out\nIpto a new field, instituting Improve\nments for local benefit and entering\nthe \"giant power\" business. The wis\ndom of this course has been repeated\nly questioned. Now we can await the\nfinal answer to all such questions\u2014\nthe result ot experience.\nMB SHAW'S KINDNESS\n[Everybody's Magazine, London.]\nA characteristic act of kindness on\nthe part of George Bernard Shaw\nwas when the play ot a young author\nwas about to be taken off after a\nshort run in order to make way for\none ot Shaw's.\nShaw went to the manager of the\ntheater and asked him it it wasn\u2019t\npossible to keep the young writer's\nplay on longer.\n\"I\u2019m losing money on It,\u201d declared\nthe manager.\n\"Well,\u201d said Shaw, \"how much\nwould you lose it you ran his play\nfor another month?\"\nWhen the manager named the sum\nShaw took out Ills checkbook and\nmade out a check tor the amount.\n\"Hold up my play and keep his on,\u201d\nhe said. \u201cThat young man shows\npromise.\" 1\nReliable Information. Shows\nTrade Improvement Ahead\nData Gained by Research Department of One of Larg\nest Public Utility Corporations in Country Re\nported to Indicate Depression Will End Next Month\nCompany Has Never Been Wrong in Its Estimates\nWall-Street Correspondence of The Republican\nNew York. Sept. 2\u2014One of the\nlargest public utility corporations In\nthe country, one serving every part\nof the country, has a very extensive\nresearch department which keeps in\nclose touch with commodity prices,\nfreight car loadings, bank clearings,\nsteel and pig iron production and oth\ner basic industries to get the trend\nof general trade. The information\ncompiled by this department finds its I\nway to a few bankers but is never\nmade public and according to the of\nficials of the company never will be.\nIt is feared that such information\nwould overstimulate general trade in\ngood times and cause unwarranted\npessimism in times of depression. This\ncompany has a record of never hav\ning been wrong in its predictions of\nwhat is ahead In general trade. A\nyear ago the information then in hand\nIndicated plainly that a slowing down\nwas ahead for general trade.\nIt is understood from reliable\nsources that the information now in\nthe hands of the public utility corpor\nation in question indicates that trade\ndepression in this country will be over\nnext month; that slow but steady im\nprovement in general trade is ahead;\nthat allowing for the normal annual\nincrease of 4 per cent in the volume\nof general trade July of 1931 will\nshow an increase of anywhere from 8\nto 10 per cent above July of 1921 when\nthe existing depression started.\nWall-street banks called loans to\nday in connection with month-end\nmoney market requirements. The re\nnewal ratfe tor call money was 2 per\ncent with 1% quoted on the outside\nmarket. The 1% per cent money, how\never, was withdrawn. Time money for\ntour to six months was firmer.\nSeek Money-Rate Trend\nWith the beginning of autumn,\nWall-street people dependent upon\nborrowed money make an effort to\ndetermine the trend of interest rates.\nUnder anything like normal condi\ntions, important factors in the money\nSituation and outlook make predic\ntions of the trend of Interest rates\nfairly accurate. Under anything like\nnormal conditions commercial loans\nbegin to expand in August and reach\na seasonal peak late in October or\naround the middle of November. The\ncombined peak of money in circula\ntion and commercial loans is reached\nin December. In a tight money mar\nket, the worst time of the year is\nexperienced in October and November,\nwith a temporary lull, and then an\nother squeeze around the end of the\nyear or the beginning of the new\nyear. In a tight money market, March\nusually is the worst month in the\nfirst half of the year, with gradual\nrelaxation until preparations start for\nthe heavy July 1 requirements.\nJudgment of what to expect in the\nmoney market with the beginning of\nthis autumn is made difficult by sev\neral factors. In the first place, be\ncause of worldwide slowing down in\ngeneral trade, commercial require\nments are comparatively small. Then,\nthe very low prices for commodities\nnow existing, reduce commercial re\nquirements. Stock market require\nments for money are also compara\ntively small. For the month just\nclosed, the turnover on the New York\nStock exchange was only 39,869,000\nshares, compared with 47,746,000 for\ntbo previous month, which was small\nWEEKLY REVIEW\nOF BOND MARKET\nClose of Vacation Season\nBrings Inquiry for High*\nGrade Issues Bidding Is\nBrisk and Volume High\nNew York, Aug. 30\u2014(AP) \u2014The bond\nmarket enters the fall period at the\npeak levels of the past two years.\nThe turn of the new month which\nsignalizes the end ot the summer va\ncation season finds the bond market\nmuch improved as a result of the in\nquiry for high grade investment issues\nby banks and other institutions. Al\nthough the volume ot business during\nthe past week was about equal to pre\nvious years, bidding was brisk at\ntimes, particularly for highly rated ob\nligations of domestic corporations, and\nduring the final week the pace of trad\ning quickened as the better tope of the\nstock market focused more attention\non stock privilege bonds.\nIn the week just closed the price\nlevel ot .bonds as measured by the av\nerages twice reached new peaks for\nthe year, and now stands about\npoints under the high point reached In\nthe spring ot 1928 before the last de\ncline started. Raiirdads, utilities and\nIndustrials all reached new highs in\nthe averages during the week. The\nbond market was strong during the\nfirst three days and then backslid as;\nrealizing gave the market an irregu\nlar appearance.\nSeveral bond men have painted a\nrosy picture of the future and predi\ncated largely on the belief that the\ncyclical movements of the past will\nbe repeated, and one prominent statis\ntical organization enme out with a\nstatement that it expected bond prices\nwould rise to the best level in 20\nyears.\nWith money rates continuing easy,\nbond brokers seo In the present sit\nuation factors which they believe will\nswing the pendulum of public interest\nto investment purchases. Seasonal de\nmands for currency may tend to in\nfluence some firming in money rates,\nbut is expected to have no more than\na temporary effect on the bond mar\nket.\nA huge sum of money, estimated be\ntween $500,000,000 and $1,000,000,000,\nbecomes available for reinvestment\nnext month and some, signs already\nhave appeared to strengthen belief\nthat a considerable portion may flow\ninto the market for fixed income se\ncurities.\nNew financing is expected to pick\nup In September, and financial circles\nhear reports of several large offerings\nfor early marketing. This may check\nthe rise in listed bonds. The volume i\nin August was small, which had a\nsalutary effect on the listed market.\nFinancing during the last week in Au\ngust totaled $67,907,000. consisting ot\nfive pieces of financing, four of which\nwere municipal Issues. The total was\nswelled through the $36,000,000 Nickel\nPlate railroad bond issue, and was\nlarger than the previous week, when\nofferings aggregated only $28,539,500.\nWILSON'S PARTIAL SUCCESS\n[Joseph Wirth, German Statesman.]\nGermany has been \"made sate for\ndemocracy\u201d and under the republic\nmay boast ot being the freest country\nn the world.\nand contrasted with 93,704,000 shares\nso- August of last year. Despite the\nactive markets of May and June on\ndeclining prices, the turnover for the\neight months of this year is only 580.-\n000,000 shares, against 726,000,000 for\nthe corresponding period of 1929.\nBank Demand Large\nBut, on the other hand, the de\nmand being made upon the banks by\ncustomers to carry securities is un\nusually large. Only recently, for the\nfirst time in the history of our banks,\nloans on securities were larger than\ncommercial loans. The extent of the\noutward flow of gold starting in July\nis another factor for uncertainty *n\nthe money situation. So, also, is the\nopen-market policy of the Federal\nReserve. The best gpess here is that\nmoney rates for the autumn and win\nter months will be firmer, but lower\nthan any recent year since 1924.\nStocks opened firm, with the new\nfast ticker operating for the first\ntime shooting ahead entirely clean\ning up in the first 10 minutes all of\nthe business accumulating over the\nextended holiday. Evidently from the\npace set at the opening it was intend\ned to show that the new ticker could\ndo on a big day. Wall street conclud\ned from the exhibition that it will be\nmany a long day before the ticker\nwill again fall as far behind the floor\nas it did last year when, during the\npanic, it kept printing quotations for\nover four hours after trading on the\nstock exchange ended for the day.\nThere was some profit taking around\nthe end of the first hour, followed by\ninactivity and then a broader, stronger\nmarket, with Steel by noon up a point\nto a new high for this movement, the\nhighest since last May. American To\nbacco B, Allied Chemical and Worth\nington were up four points or more,\nthe last named on rumors of a coming\nsplitU\u00df four for one. Ths rails and\npublic utilities did better. Consol\nidated Gas was one of the strongest\nstocks on the list.\nGillette Was the only soft stock in\nthe early trading. Since the merger\nnegotiations with Auto Strop were\nabandoned a week or so ago, Gillette\nhas been heavily sold. Only a tew\ndays ago Auto Strop increased its\ndividend, leading Wall street to the\nconclusion that Gillette will have to\npay a higher price than at wants to\nfor Auto Strop or else meet very\nsevere competition.\nWhat happened in retail trade last\nmonth is shown by today's August\nsale figures for Montgomery Ward.\nThe total was only 320,966,000 against\n$24,955,000 a year ago. This is a de\ncrease of 15.9 per cent. For the eight\nmonths the figures are $169,820,000\nagainst $167,571,000, an Increase of\n1.3 per cent. The management of\nthe company explained that for Au\ngust of last year there .was an in\ncrease in sales of 46 per cent over\n1928, due partly to widespread ac\ntivity in general trade and partly to\nthe new plan then adopted of pre\npaying freight. This plan has since\nbeen abandoned by both Montgomery\nWard and Sears Roebuck.\nNational Bellas Hess which now\nincludes \u2019the old National Cloak\nSult company, reports for August\nsales of $1,933,000 against $3,347,000\nfor last year. This is a decrease of 42\nper cent. For the eight months the\nfigures are $22,626,000 against $31,-\n986,000 for the same period of last\nyear, a decrease of 29.3 per cent.\nR. L. BARNUM.\njMILUONS SUPPORT\nLAND BANK SYSTEM\nTreasury Secretary Sends\nLetter to Group of Bankers\nActive in Government In\nstitution Securities\nNew York, Aug. 28\u2014(AP)\u2014-Secre\ntary Mellon in a letter to a group of\nbankers that has sold Federal Land\nbank bonds to the public, states that\nthe Federal Land bank system has\ndemonstrated its fundamental sound\nness, and investors in the banks\u2019\nbonds should not be disturbed by\nfalse or misleading information over\nthe agricultural situation.\nThe letter was written In reference\nto a report being prepared by the\nsyndicate managers on the banks and\ntheir bonds, an advance copy of\nwhich was sent to Mr Mellon.' The\nbanking group includes Alexander\nBrown Sons, Harris Forbes Co.,\nLee, Higginson Co.. Brown Broth\ners, the National City company and\nthe Guaranty company, as syndicate\nmanagers.\nMr Mellon writes that the report,\nreviewing the land bank situation\nafter 13 years, is appropriate and\n\u201ctimely in view of the current dis\ncussion of adverse agricultural con\nditions, and also should be helpful to\nrefute much of the misinformation\nthat has been circulated recently with\nrespect to these banks and their se\ncurities, and which undoubtedly has\nmisled, and therefore disturbed, some\ninvestors.\u201d\nHe explains that the drouth situa\ntion is temporary and confined to cer\ntain circumscribed areas, and the di\nversity ot conditions that exist in the\ngreat expanse of the country\u2019s terri\ntory Is an element ot strength in\nthe land banks.\n\"The Federal Land banks are\npermanent institutions, designed to\nfunction in good times and bad,\u201d he\ncontinues, \"they constitute a great\nmutual and cooperative organization\nthat covers the entire country, and\neach bank, in addition to being pri\nmarily liable tor its own bonds, is\nliable, under the conditions stated in\nthe law, for the principal ot. and in\nterest on, the farm loan bonds issued\nby all the other Federal Land banks.\n\"These bonds issued by the Federal\nLand banks constitute a sound, tax\nfree security, and investors should\nnot be disturbed by false or mislead\ning information The achievements\nand service ot the system have dem\nonstrated Its fundamental soundness\nand usefulness.\"\nSALE OF MONORAIL\nSECURITIES BARRED\nFrom Our Special Reporter\nBoston. Aug. 29\u2014Director John C.\nHull ot the securities division of state\ndepartment ot public utilities today\nprohibited the sale ot securities ot the\nMonorail Transportation System, Inc.,\nIn this state. In ills decision, Hull\nstates the officers ot the company re\nfused to file additional Information\nthat the division deemed necessary to\nenable it to ascertain whether the sale\nof such securities would be fraudulent\nor would desuit in fraud. The officers\nwere given until July 15, last, to file\nsuch data.\nNew York Stock Market\nI Prev\nSales (la 100 s) High. Low. Close. CFse.\nA\n1 Abitibi Power 22 22 22 22\n1 do pl 75 75 75\n4 Adam- Express 27 l 27%\nI Adams Millis 20% 20% 20\u2019\nJ Add Internal 32 32 32 2\u2019%\n4 Air Reduction ..124% 123% 124% 125\n4 Airway El Ap 18% 17% 17% 17%\n3 Ajax Rubber 1% 1 J\ni I\u201d Alaska Juneau 5% 5% 7%\n2 Albany PWP 10% b\u00bb% 10%\nHl Alleghany Corp 22% 22% 22 a 22%\n20 Allied Chern ...,278 s 274 274 274\n1 do pf 126 ]2G J2O\nAllis Chalmers 50% 34% .71%\nG Amerada 24% 24 24 24%\nlAm Agri Ch 5% 5% 5%\n3 do pf 33 35 34:-,\nI Am Dank Note 81 81 RI\n4 Am Bosch Mag 33% 32% 32% 32%\n4 Am Er Bove ri 18% 17% 17% 18%\